  For equation
  \begin{align*}
  \alpha
P_{\mathbb{S}^n}v_{\alpha}+2Q_{g_{\mathbb{S}^n}}=2Q_{g_{\mathbb{S}^n}}e^{nv_{\alpha}},
  \end{align*}
  we have proved that: (1) suppose $\alpha>1$ and $n\geq3$ or $\alpha\in
(1-\epsilon_0, 1)$ and $n=2m\geq4$, then $v_{\alpha}\equiv0$; (2) if
$n=2m\geq4$, for any $\epsilon>0$, the following set
  \begin{align*}
  \mathcal{S}_{\epsilon}=\left\{v_{\alpha}\Big|\alpha
P_{\mathbb{S}^n}v_{\alpha}+2Q_{g_{\mathbb{S}^n}}=2Q_{g_{\mathbb{S}^n}}e^{nv_{\alpha}}\,\,\mathrm{and}\,\,
\alpha\in \left(\frac{1}{2}+\epsilon,1\right)\right\}
  \end{align*}
  is compact in $C^{\infty}(\S^n)$ topology; (3) if $\alpha_i\to\frac{1}{2}$,
then $\{v_{\alpha_i}\}_{i=1}^{+\infty}$ either is uniformly bounded or up to a
subsequence, it has two concentration points $\{x_1, -x_1\}\subset\mathbb{S}^n$
and
  \begin{align*}
  e^{nv_i}\mathrm{d} V_{g_{\mathbb{S}^n}}\rightharpoonup
\frac{\delta_{x_1}+\delta_{-x_1}}{2}|\mathbb{S}^n|.
  \end{align*}
